T1  - Employee Voice and Employee Retention
AU  - Spencer, Daniel G.
Y1  - 1986/09/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256220
DO  - 10.5465/256220
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 488
EP  - 502
VL  - 29
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigates the relationship between the extent to which employees have opportunities to voice dissatisfaction and voluntary turnover in 111 short-term, general care hospitals. Results show that, whether or not a union is present, high numbers of mechanisms for employee voice are associated with high retention rates. Implications for theory and research as well as management practice are discussed.
AB  - This study investigates the relationship between the extent to which employees have opportunities to voice dissatisfaction and voluntary turnover in 111 short-term, general care hospitals. Results show that, whether or not a union is present, high numbers of mechanisms for employee voice are associated with high retention rates. Implications for theory and research as well as management practice are discussed.
